-- Italian Stocks: Amplifon, Azimut, Bulgari, Iren, STMicro Move in Milan
-- Francesca Cinelli
-- 2010-07-20T07:54:33Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-20/finmeccanica-l-espresso-popolare-milano-may-move-italy-equity-preview.html

          
          
             Italy’s benchmark  FTSE MIB  Index
rose 65.67, or 0.3 percent, to 20,183.21 as of 9:43 a.m. in
Milan, its first gain in five sessions.  
 The following stocks were among the most active in the
Italian market today.  
 Amplifon SpA  (AMP IM), the world’s largest hearing-aid
distributor, lost 8.5 cents, or 2 percent, to 4.11 euros. Audika
SA, Europe’s second-largest hearing-aid distributor, plummeted
in Paris trading after posting quarterly results.  
 Azimut Holding SpA  (AZM IM) rose for the first time in
three sessions, gaining 6.5 cents, or 1 percent, to 6.62 euros.
Italy’s largest independent fund manager was raised to “buy”
from “add” at Banca IMI.  
 Bulgari SpA  (BUL IM) advanced 12 cents, or 2 percent, to
6.04 euros, snapping a four-day loss after Hermes International
SCA raised its 2010 sales growth target to 10 percent to 12
percent from a previous forecast of at least 5 percent.
 Luxottica Group SpA  (LUX IM) rose 0.9 percent to 19.11 euros.  
 Iren SpA  (IRE IM), the municipal utility created by the
merger of Iride SpA and Enia SpA, increased 1.4 cents, or 1.1
percent, to 1.26 euros, its first gain in five sessions, after
Mediobanca Securities initiated coverage of the stock with an
“outperform” recommendation.  
 STMicroelectronics NV  (STM IM), Europe’s largest chipmaker,
retreated for a fourth session, falling 5.5 cents, or 0.8
percent, to 6.56 euros. Texas Instruments Inc., the second-
largest U.S. chipmaker, reported second-quarter profit and sales
that fell short of analysts’ estimates.  
